originContent: An MCP (Model Context Protocol) server for interacting with a Paperless-NGX API server. This server provides tools for managing documents, tags, correspondents, and document types in your Paperless-NGX instance.
translatedContent: An MCP (Model Context Protocol) server for interacting with a Paperless-NGX API server. This server provides tools for managing documents, tags, correspondents, and document types in your Paperless-NGX instance.

originContent: To install Paperless NGX MCP Server for Claude Desktop automatically via [Smithery](https://smithery.ai/server/@nloui/paperless-mcp):

translatedContent: 2. Add it to your Claude's MCP configuration:

originContent: 2. Click your username in the top right
translatedContent: 2. Click your username in the top right

originContent: 4. Click the circular arrow button to generate a new token
translatedContent: 4. Click the circular arrow button to generate a new token

originContent: 4. Replace the placeholders in your MCP config:
translatedContent: 4. Replace the placeholders in your MCP config:

originContent: That's it! Now you can ask Claude to help you manage your Paperless-NGX documents.

originContent: Want to contribute or modify the server? Here's what you need to know:
translatedContent: Want to contribute or modify the server? Here's what you need to know:

originContent: - [litemcp](https://github.com/wong2/litemcp): A TypeScript framework for building MCP servers
translatedContent: - [litemcp](https://github.com/wong2/litemcp): A TypeScript framework for building MCP servers

originContent: This MCP server implements endpoints from the Paperless-NGX REST API. For more details about the underlying API, see the [official documentation](https://docs.paperless-ngx.com/api/).
translatedContent: This MCP server implements endpoints from the Paperless-NGX REST API. For more details about the underlying API, see the [official documentation](https://docs.paperless-ngx.com/api/).

originContent: The MCP server can be run in two modes:
translatedContent: The MCP server can be run in two modes:

originContent: This is the default mode. The server communicates over stdio, suitable for CLI and direct integrations.
translatedContent: This is the default mode. The server communicates over stdio, suitable for CLI and direct integrations.

originContent: To run the server as an HTTP service, use the `--http` flag. You can also specify the port with `--port` (default: 3000). This mode requires [Express](https://expressjs.com/) to be installed (it is included as a dependency).
translatedContent: To run the server as an HTTP service, use the `--http` flag. You can also specify the port with `--port` (default: 3000). This mode requires [Express](https://expressjs.com/) to be installed (it is included as a dependency).

originContent: - The MCP API will be available at `POST /mcp` on the specified port.
translatedContent: - The MCP API will be available at `POST /mcp` on the specified port.

originContent: - Each request is handled statelessly, following the [StreamableHTTPServerTransport](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/typescript-sdk) pattern.
translatedContent: - Each request is handled statelessly, following the [StreamableHTTPServerTransport](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/typescript-sdk) pattern.

originContent: - GET and DELETE requests to `/mcp` will return 405 Method Not Allowed.
translatedContent: - GET and DELETE requests to `/mcp` will return 405 Method Not Allowed.
